               <italic>Drosophila</italic>. Finally, in mammals, L-leucine and sucrose                    administration induced digit regeneration in adult mice, including dramatically                    from mid-phalangeal amputation. The conserved effect of L-leucine and                    insulin/sugar suggests a key role for energetic parameters in regeneration                    induction. The simplicity by which nutrient supplementation can induce appendage                    regeneration provides a testable hypothesis across animals.</p>            </abstract>            <kwd-group kwd-group-type="research-organism">                <title>Research organism</title>                <kwd><italic>D. melanogaster</italic></kwd>                <kwd>Mouse</kwd>            </kwd-group>            <funding-group>                <award-group id="par-1">                    <funding-source><institution-wrap>                            <institution-id institution-id-type="FundRef">http://dx.doi.org/10.13039/100000913</institution-id>                            <institution>James S. McDonnell Foundation</institution>                        </institution-wrap></funding-source>                    <award-id>Complex Systems Science,220020365</award-id>                    <principal-award-recipient><name>                            <surname>Goentoro</surname>                            <given-names>Lea</given-names>                        </name></principal-award-recipient>                </award-group>                <award-group id="par-2">                    <funding-source><institution-wrap>                            <institution-id institution-id-type="FundRef">http://dx.doi.org/10.13039/100000001</institution-id>                            <institution>National Science Foundation</institution>                        </institution-wrap></funding-source>                    <award-id>Graduate Research Fellowship,1144469</award-id>                    <principal-award-recipie